dency to frame rural and remote locations as emblematic of authentic or "real" Indigeneity and as central to the survival of Indigenous cultures and societies. While such a perspective may support Indigenous struggles for territory and recognition as distinct peoples, it fails to account for large swaths of contemporary Indigenous realities, not the least of which is the increased presence of Indigenous people and communities in cities. The chapters in this volume explore the implications of urbanization on the production of distinctive Indigenous identities in Canada, the United States, New Zealand, and Australia. Instead of viewing urban experiences in terms of assimilation and social and cultural disruption, this book demonstrates the resilience, creativity, and complexity of the urban Indigenous presence, both in Canada and internationally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxEthnic identity. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxEthnic identity. 0aUrban Indigenous peopleszCanada. 0aUrban Indigenous peoples. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAndersen, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndersen, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBelanger, Yale D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClatworthy, Stewart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoombes, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenop, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHokowhitu, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Jay T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKukutai, Tahu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g